@Emerald Henry
You’ve done a lot of noticing and wondering.  You comment on that maybe the low cost of fast food makes it attractive to people in lower- income countries.  What else may attract these new customers to fast food restaurants?  Also, one of your comments is “Fast food is becoming an epidemic around the world.”  What do you mean by “epidemic”?  Maybe it could be taken both literally and figuratively.  Let us know what you think.
How about a catchy headline?

@SDCI PIVOT
@SDCI PIVOT
Noticing and wondering leads to more in depth noticings and wonderings.

You came to a very important conclusion of of why the US has low wealth and fast-food sales growth.  How about the reverse?  Notice which countries have increased greatly for both of these quantitative variables.  Combine that with what you see in the scatterplot.  Are there other conclusions you could make?

I wonder what the consequences are of lower-middle and upper-middle income countries having increasing fast-food sales.  What are the positive and negative consequences?

Do you now have other catchy headlines that capture the main ideas of this graph?
